        "text": "\n\nThe Russian attack on Ukraine is obviously more than a war. As if a war were not already one of the most terrible things that people can do to other people, this one is also a \"turning point in time\". That is how German Chancellor Olaf Scholz (SPD) described it. According to the dictionary, a turning point is \"the end of an epoch or era and the beginning of a new time. In between, there is usually a great catastrophe, a huge break, the downfall of a world. In the turn of the times there are both, apocalypse and decision struggle. What does someone want who conjures up the turn of the times? Downfall, decision, new beginning - all in one, perhaps.\n\nA narrative, after all, comes to an end, and at the same time there is a great associative confusion, ghosts come from the past, the scenario of a third world war is close at hand, fear, hunger and cold seem conceivable again even in one's own body, or at least painful gasoline prices and noodle shortages. The downfall of a country looms, but also the downfall of a world order. And if it wasn't an \"order,\" perhaps it was a kind of balance, an enterprise, or at least a space for desires, projections, profits. A so-called narrative, in fact. The third narrative of the apocalypse in recent times, between pandemic and global warming.\n"
